	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>What is Crystal Ball Diplomacy anyway?</b><br>
	Basically, Crystal Ball Diplomacy is a standard game of Diplomacy (on any
	game map, etc.) in which you cannot see what happens on each turn
	until your moves for the <i>next</i> turn are written.
	Each player must guess or deduce what the board will look like to have
	the best chance of successfully ordering his units to meet his objectives.
	Think of it as having to sit far from the battles and have your orders
	to the armies and navies dispatched by carrier pigeon, and needing to
	conduct a complete campaign that way.

<P><b>Okay, but what is the game of Diplomacy?</b><br>
	If you asked this question, you have my sympathy that you managed to
	live long enough to form intelligent questions without becoming
	acquainted with -- nay, addicted to -- Diplomacy.  I won't answer the
	question here, but will instead refer you to the Internet home page
	of the Diplomacy hobby, <a href=<POUCH>>The
	Diplomatic Pouch</a>, where you can find the answer you seek.
	The Pouch is chock full of more information on The Game
	than you can digest in one sitting -- one place to start is
	<a href=<POUCH>/Welcome.html>The Pouch's "Welcome"
	page</a>, where I wrote a quickie overview of Diplomacy itself.
	<i>(Head for The Pouch now, because
	the rest of these questions are answered assuming that you are familiar
	with Diplomacy, and most Crystal Ball players cut their teeth on the
	standard game first before trying to deal with the possibility that their
	own units won't obey orders.)</i>
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

