	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>How do I issue orders if I don't know where my
pieces will be located?</b><br>
	If you issue an order for a unit that isn't there (for example,
	if you order an army in Paris to move to Burgundy, but there is
	no army in Paris when the time comes for your orders to be issued),
	the order has no effect.  Perhaps this is because the army already moved
	to Burgundy on the previous turn (you had thought perhaps it would
	bounce) -- if so, hopefully you have also issued an order for an army
	in Burgundy in case this is indeed what happened.

<P><b>Looks like I'll have to guess where my units will
end up.  No problem.  I'll just issue an order for a unit in every single
place on the board and those that are mine will follow those orders.
Can't I just do this?</b><br>
	No, you can't just do this.  If you could, everyone would do it, and
	what fun would that be?
	You need to make your best attempt to learn where your units will be,
	because the number of wrong guesses you can make on a turn is limited.
	<P>
	Each player's order list can contain only a certain number of
	orders that will be "considered."  After that number, any orders
	appearing later in the list are completely ignored.
	<P>
	The number of
	orders that will be "considered" is the same as the number of supply
	centers held by the largest power on the board.
	<P>
	So if you are the largest power on the board and you want to issue
	an order to every one of your units, you have no room for error.
	You have to know (or guess correctly) where every one of your units
	will be if you truly wish to get an order to each and every one of them.
	By contrast, a smaller power can issue more orders than he has units,
	which allows him more of a chance to "find" and issue orders to each
	of his units.

<P><b>So you're saying I always have one set of
orders that I've pre-issued, and they're "locked-in," right?  Well,
what if it turns out I was wrong about where my units ended up.  Can
I change my "locked-in" orders?</b><br>
	No.  That's why they're called "locked-in."  There is, however, one
	(and only one) exception.
	<P>
	You <i>will</i> be allowed to <i>rearrange</i> the sequence of the
	orders in your "locked-in" list for the first Fall phase of the game
	(that is, you may add no new orders, and remove no currently listed
	orders), if and only if the GameMaster allows you to do so.
	You must request permission to do this, and the GameMaster must agree
	that your reason for the request is because it is apparent from your
	order list that it was written in ignorance of Rule 3.1.
	<P>
	Rule 3.1 limits the number of orders that each player will have
	at his useful disposal.  Here is an example of a Fall 1901 order
	list written in obvious ignorance of Rule 3.1.
	<dl><dd><tt>
		F ENG S A PIC - BEL<br>
		F BRE - ENG<br>
		A BUR S A PIC - BEL<br>
		A MAR - BUR<br>
		A PIC - BEL</tt></dd></dl>
	The obvious intention of this order list is to provide as much
	support as possible to a move from Picardy to Belgium.  However,
	by virtue of Rule 3.1, the fifth and subsequent orders in the list
	are completely ignored, so the Picardy army will not receive
	the order to move to Belgium.  The French player wanted to cover both
	his uncertainties (that his Springtime moves to the English Channel
	and to Burgundy may have bounced) but he cannot.  If the GameMaster
	notices this type of order list, or if he is requested by the owner
	of such an order list, he would allow the player to re-sequence the
	orders in the list.
	<P>
	Notice that this exception is made <i>only</i> for the order list
	submitted for the <i>first Fall movement phase</i> of the game, and
	that it allows the player <i>only</i> to re-sequence the orders he
	had already submitted.

<P><b>What happens if I list more than one order for a
particular unit?</b><br>
	The unit will follow the <i>last</i> order that you give it before using
	up your allotment of "considered" orders.  The earlier ones will be marked
	<tt>revoked</tt>.

<P><b>What if a unit doesn't receive any order at all?
What will it do?</b><br>
	It will <tt>HOLD</tt>.

<P><b>Will the other players see my order list?  Will
they see how confused I am and/or what I would have done to them had my
units been in place?  Or will they only see the results of the moves,
and wonder why so many of my units were ordered to <tt>HOLD</tt> and
what I was planning had I not been so wrong about where they are?</b><br>
	In (most) Crystal Ball games that allow press, the order lists are
	kept secret until the end of the game.  A player can see his own
	order lists going back to the beginning of the game, but has no access
	to the order list of any of the other players.  Once the game is
	finished, though, all order lists become public knowledge.
	<p>
	In games with<i>out</i> press, however, the order lists <i>are publicly
	broadcast</i> with the results of each movement phase.  Players <i>do</i>
	see each and every order listed in all other players' order lists --
	including those that are marked <tt>no&nbsp;unit</tt> and those that
	fall after the limit of "considered" orders and which are therefore marked
	<tt>ignored</tt>.  This makes the order list a tool for communication
	among players (although the signals you may try to send using your
	ignored orders are going to be a season out-of date by the time they
	are read!).
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

