		<tr><td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" class="grey" align=center><a name="3"></a><b>Proxies</b></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>It sounds like if a smaller power has a good idea of
where all his units are, he will have slots in his order list for which he has
no use.  If I'm a larger or more confused power,
is it possible for me to "borrow" some of those unused slots from him to
help me out?</b><br>
	Yes, it is.  You can proxy one or more of your units to another power
	in hopes that he will be willing to devote extra room in his
	list to help you out by giving your unit an order.  For example,
	if you make a move from Brest to the English Channel and you are not
	sure whether that move will succeed, you would like in your next
	order list to issue an order both for a fleet in the English Channel
	and one in Brest (just in case).  However, if you do not have room in your
	"considered" orders, you could allow either or both of these
	orders to be given by proxy by another player.

<P><b>Wait a minute!  What's the use in that?  Issuing a
proxy order still takes up one of my "considered" orders, doesn't it?</b><br>
	No, it doesn't.  Proxy orders are <i>not</i> counted under 
	"considered" orders limit discussed above.
	Instead, they are counted <i><u>and limited</u></i> separately.  
	<P>
	Each player may issue only a certain number of proxy orders on a turn.
	This number is the number of supply centers owned by the
	<i><b>smallest</b></i> uneliminated power in the game.  Contrast this
	with the maximum number of "considered" <i>non-</i>proxy orders,
	which is the supply count of the <i>largest</i> power in the game.
	<P>
	This separate limit makes it worth the while of the largest
	power on the board to see that the smallest power is not so small
	that the leader has insufficient proxies to offer to his allies.  However,
	it also makes it in the interests of the smaller powers to shrink
	one power, located far from the leader if possible, to near elimination,
	thus limiting the leader's proxy capability (assuming he is
	using that capability well in concert with a loyal ally).

<P><b>How do I issue a proxy order?</b><br>
	List the unit, then a <tt>P</tt> (or the word <tt>PROXY</tt>, etc.),
	and then the <i>full name</i> of the power to be given the proxy.  For
	example: <ul><dd><tt>F BRE P ENGLAND</tt></dd></ul>

<P><b>What happens if I proxy a unit to another player
and that other player does not issue an order to the unit?</b><br>
	The unit will <tt>HOLD</tt>.

<P><b>What happens if I proxy a unit to another player
and he in turn proxies it to yet another player (or back to me)?</b><br>
	Again, the unit will <tt>HOLD</tt>.  The power receiving a
	proxy from the player who actually owns a unit must either
	order the unit or leave it unordered (to <tt>HOLD</tt>).  If
	he instead issues a proxy order for the unit, it will be marked
	<tt>reProxy</tt> and rendered invalid.
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

