		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>What if I wish to <i>support</i> the move of a fleet in
Constantinople to a particular coast of Bulgaria?  The Website
is not letting me enter the order.  How do I do it?</b><br>
	You cannot.  You may offer support for the fleet to move to Bulgaria,
	but not to a specific <i>coast</i> of Bulgaria.  This is the proper
	implementation of the Diplomacy rules -- support is directed to a
	<i>space</i>, not to a specific <i>coast</i>.

<P><b>What if I don't know whether I will have an
army or a fleet in a certain place, but I wish to give it the same
order?  Can I omit the unit type?</b><br>
	No, you cannot.  If, for example, you wish to use your
	London unit (whose type -- army or fleet -- you don't know)
	to support a unit in Wales,
	you would need to use up two of your "considered" orders to ensure that
	the unit receives your order:
	<ul><dd><tt>A LON S F WAL<br><dd>F LON S F WAL</tt></ul>
	<i>(Note that if you are unsure which type of unit will be in Wales,
	you <b><u>can</u></b> omit <b><u>its</u></b> unit type -- see the answer
	to the next question for an example of this.)</i>


<P><b>Do I need to include the type of unit <i>receiving</i>
a support? Or can I say I wish to support a unit no matter what its type
might happen to be (in case I don't know which type of unit will be there)?
</b><br>
	The answer to the first question is no, and to the second question is
	yes.  You may specify a support (or convoy) order that does not
	specify the type (army or fleet) of the other involved unit.  For
	example:
	<ul><dd><tt>A BEL S GAS - BRE</tt></ul>
	will be valid for a move to Brest made from Gascony by either an army
	or a fleet, and
	<ul><dd><tt>A BUR S GAS</tt></ul>
	will be valid to support whichever type of unit (army or fleet) happened
	to be in Gascony.
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

