	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>
How does the first turn work?</b><br>
	Before the orders for the first turn are processed, all players must have
	entered orders for <i>both</i> the first and second movement phases.  No
	player may enter orders for the second movement phase until <i>after
	<u>all</u> players have entered orders for the first phase.</i>
	<P>
	When the final player to
	enter orders for the first phase submits valid orders -- <i>and as
	<u>soon</u> as he does so!</i> -- the orders for all players are "locked
	down" and notice is sent to all players indicating that orders for the
	second movement phase may be entered.

<P><b>What about retreat and adjustment phases?  Do I 
"forecast" orders for those phases of the game too?</b><br>
	No.  All of a player's retreat, build, and remove orders are issued
	"in real time," as they occur.  That is, you would issue a Spring
	retreat order only after the Spring movement phase actually happens,
	which is after you have "locked in" your Fall movement orders.  
	In retreat and adjustment phases, therefore,
	a Crystal Ball game is just like a standard Diplomacy game.
	Just as you enter your movement phase order lists at the Website,
	you can issue your retreat and adjustment phase orders here too.

<P><b>
Will moves process before the deadline if all players get their (next)
order list submitted?
</b><br>
	The short answer is, "Yes; assuming no player has set his <i>wait flag</i>."
	The complete answer to this and other similar questions can be found on the
	Webpage that answers the
	<a href=<URL>?page=Questions>Common Questions About the DPjudge</a>.
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

